{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570017"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:36:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:36:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22636"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22636"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.18,0.1,0.34,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113209"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15583"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95236"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"3033"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13199"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46042"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113209"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman of Taiwanese ethnicity presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis and severe depression. Her regular medications are methotrexate, folic acid and sertraline. She smokes 10 cigarettes per day and drinks alcohol occasionally. She works as a pharmacy assistant and lives with her partner. She has a family history of premature menopause in her mother and aunt. Her most recent eGFR was 72 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 74/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her body mass index is 27 kg/m\u00b2. Recent blood tests show a total cholesterol of 5.5 mmol/L (3.5-5.5) and HDL of 1.1 mmol/L (1.0-2.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou use the Australian cardiovascular disease risk calculator and estimate her risk of a cardiovascular event in the next five years as 4%. You are considering whether this patient\u0027s risk profile should be reclassified and whether any further testing is needed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors would reclassify this patient\u0027s cardiovascular risk as high?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Her renal function","Her ethnicity","Her family history","Her psychiatric comorbidity","Her cholesterol results"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian absolute cardiovascular disease risk calculator is used to estimate an individual\u0027s five-year risk of developing cardiovascular disease based on established risk factors. The 2023 Australian guideline for assessing and managing cardiovascular disease risk includes specific reclassification factors that may prompt clinicians to consider upgrading a patient\u0027s risk category, particularly when the calculated risk falls close to the upper threshold of the low or intermediate risk categories.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHer psychiatric comorbidity\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. Severe mental illness, including severe depression, is specifically included as a reclassification factor in the 2023 Australian guidelines. Severe mental illnesses such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, and major depressive disorder are recognised to increase cardiovascular risk through multiple mechanisms including lifestyle factors, medication effects, and biological pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHer renal function\u003C/strong\u003E could be a reclassification factor if she had chronic kidney disease. The 2023 guidelines specify that an eGFR \u0026lt;45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 or elevated uACR (\u226525 mg/mmol for males or \u226535 mg/mmol for females) would prompt reclassification. However, this patient\u0027s eGFR of 72 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 represents only mild reduction and without evidence of proteinuria, would not meet criteria for reclassification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEthnicity\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed a reclassification factor in the 2023 guidelines, however, individuals of Taiwanese ethnicity generally have a lower baseline risk of cardiovascular disease compared with the high-risk ethnic groups specified (including Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, M\u0101ori and Pacific Islander peoples, and people from South Asian backgrounds).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHer family history\u003C/strong\u003E of premature menopause is not included as a reclassification factor in the Australian CVD risk calculator. Family history of premature CVD (defined as CVD in a first-degree relative: males \u0026lt;55 years, females \u0026lt;65 years) would be a reclassification factor, but premature menopause is not.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHer cholesterol results\u003C/strong\u003E are already incorporated into the standard risk calculation and would not be used for reclassification. The calculator uses total cholesterol and HDL cholesterol values as part of the primary risk assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther reclassification factors in the 2023 Australian guidelines include the coronary artery calcium score. In this case, the patient\u0027s severe depression represents the only factor present that would prompt consideration of risk reclassification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Australian cardiovascular disease risk calculator includes severe mental illness as a factor that may reclassify cardiovascular risk.","Moderate to severe chronic kidney disease is also a reclassification factor in the 2023 Australian guidelines."],"references":["Australian absolute cardiovascular disease risk calculator. In: National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator","Goldfarb M, De Hert M, Detraux J, Di Palo K, Munir H, Music S, Pi\u00f1a I, Ringen PA. Severe Mental Illness and Cardiovascular Disease: JACC State-of-the-Art Review. J Am Coll Cardiol. 2022 Aug 30;80(9):918-933. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36007991/","Nelson MR, Banks E, Brown A, Chow CK, Peiris DP, Stocks NP, Davies Ao R, Raffoul N, Kalman L, Bradburn E, Jennings G. 2023 Australian guideline for assessing and managing cardiovascular disease risk. Med J Aust. 2024 May 20;220(9):482-490. Available from: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.5694/mja2.52280"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95236"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22636"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95236","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95236"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T13:16:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:16:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15583"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113209"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,